As of 1 OCT the Real is .316. Last October it traded in a range of of .3067 to .3122. Yet, earlier in the year the ongoing political scandal caused a 7% hit to the currency. If another political hit occurs, it could take the value to 2.95753. These sudden shocks tend to find near-term recovery. Hence, the risk is that another scandal hits the value days before the forecast closes.

Based on general news and GJP consensus.

Key determinant of exchange rate movements during this short timeframe: investor sentiment, which is most likely to be affected by developments on the government's economic reform programme (positive news being likely to strengthen the real). Progress on pensions reform before end of October now looks unlikely following President Temer's second indictment but it seems this has already been factored into expectations (https://www.ft.com/content/78dfa0e6-98fd-11e7-a652-cde3f882dd7b) with markets optimistic that pensions reform would pick up pace again by the end of the year. 2018 election prospects also relevant to market sentiment but very early days as yet. On this basis, feels unlikely that the next 1.5 months will bring sharp movements of the kind seen in May or July this year, and would guess that investors are likely to keep leaning on the optimistic side.

Otherwise, there are likely few short-term market or economic conditions that would affect any significant move.

The peak of inflation in Brazil in the last five years were the months surrounding the impeachment of President Rousseff, with an exchange rate of around 3.9 Brazilian Reals to 1 US dollar. Since her impeachment, currency deflation began in Brazil and the Real has stabilized just above 3.0. The country is stable enough to avoid major currency swings in a two month period.
